The Abia State chapter of the All Progressives Congress (APC) has adopted Ikechukwu Henry Ikoh as its candidate for the post of National Vice Chairman (Southeast), ahead of the party’s national convention on Saturday. A letter, dated March 17, 2022, and addressed to Imo State Governor Hope Uzodimma, which was sighted by our correspondent, was signed by 14 eminent members of the party. They include Uchechukwu Sampson Ogah (Minister of State, Mines and Steel); Senator Chris Adighije; Senator Nkechi Nwaogu; Emeka Wogu  (former Minister of Labour and Productivity), and Stanley Ohajuruka. The five-paragraph letter, titled: Adoption of Chief Ikechukwu Henry Ikoh as Our Candidate for the Post of National Vice Chairman, South East, reads: “Your Excellency, if you could recall, a delegation of stakeholders of Abia State APC paid you a visit on March 4, 2022, after her meeting on March 3, 2022, to solicit your support for the position of the National Vice Chairman Southeast to be ceded to Abia State, which your response was in the affirmative.   Benefits of American Corner, by U.S Ambassador     Commission may sanction agencies not implementing minimum…     EFCC chair: nothing political about Obiano’s arrest   Read Also: Buni hails protocols c’ttee says all now set for APC National Convention “We wish to convey to you that the Abia State APC stakeholders, having deliberated in several meetings over the position of the National Vice Chairman Southeast, resolved unanimously to adopt and forward the name of Chief Ikechukwu Henry Ikoh as our candidate for the National Vice Chairman Southeast.” Following the development, Ikoh has purchased his nomination/expression of interest forms, and has submitted same back to the APC national secretariat in Abuja. In a campaign flyer, Ikoh said a vote for him by the delegates was a “vote for generational change; for capacity, and for humanity”. Ikoh, who is from Ahuwa Oboro in Ikwuano Local Government Area of Abia State, was Commissioner for Industry and founder of Harmony Foam Nigeria Limited.